.TH "analyze-x86" "1" "2026-06-08" "analyze-x86 1.0+git20181231" ""
.hy
.SH NAME
.PP
analyze-x86 - analyze an x86 binary for instruction set usage
.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
\f[B]analyze-x86\f[R] \f[I]binary\f[R]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
\f[B]analyze-x86\f[R] disassembles an x86 ELF binary using
\f[B]objdump\f[R](1) and counts how many instructions from each x86
instruction set extension are present.
It reports the detected instruction class counts along with a total
instruction count, making it easy to determine the minimum CPU
instruction set required to execute the binary.
.SH ARGUMENTS
.TP
\f[I]binary\f[R]
Path to the x86 or x86-64 ELF binary to analyze.
.SH OUTPUT
.PP
Each line of output is tab-separated and has the form:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
binary<TAB>class<TAB>count
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Where \f[I]binary\f[R] is the path passed on the command line,
\f[I]class\f[R] is one of the detected instruction set names listed
below, and \f[I]count\f[R] is the number of instructions belonging to
that class.
A final line with class \f[B]total\f[R] gives the total number of
instructions disassembled.
.PP
Only classes with a non-zero count are printed.
.SS Detected instruction sets
.PP
The following instruction classes are recognized, in detection order:
.PP
\f[B]cpuid\f[R], \f[B]nop\f[R], \f[B]call\f[R], \f[B]i486\f[R],
\f[B]i586\f[R], \f[B]i686\f[R], \f[B]3dnow!\f[R], \f[B]3dnowext\f[R],
\f[B]mmx\f[R], \f[B]sse\f[R], \f[B]sse2\f[R], \f[B]sse3\f[R],
\f[B]ssse3\f[R], \f[B]sse4.1\f[R], \f[B]sse4.2\f[R], \f[B]sse4a\f[R],
\f[B]aes\f[R], \f[B]avx\f[R], \f[B]avx2\f[R]
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
\f[B]0\f[R]
Success, or the binary contains no instructions.
.TP
\f[B]1\f[R]
Wrong number of arguments, failure to invoke \f[B]objdump\f[R](1), or an
I/O error while reading its output.
.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
Analyze a system binary:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
analyze-x86 /usr/bin/ls
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Analyze all ELF binaries in a directory and sort by SSE4.2 usage:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
for f in /usr/bin/*; do analyze-x86 \[dq]$f\[dq] 2>/dev/null; done \[rs]
    | awk -F\[aq]\[rs]t\[aq] \[aq]$2==\[dq]sse4.2\[dq]{print $3, $1}\[aq] | sort -rn | head
\f[R]
.fi
.SH SEE ALSO
.PP
\f[B]objdump\f[R](1), \f[B]readelf\f[R](1), \f[B]file\f[R](1)
.SH BUGS
.PP
